 to try this, but don&#8217;t have a slow cooker and would like to get a better understanding of the alternatives. This looks yummy!</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=66868#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-66868\", \"66868\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\n\t<li class=\"comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1\" id=\"comment-66869\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\">Erin</cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/#comment-66869\">07.16.12 at 8:16 am</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>Gwen- the slow cooker just works as an insulator. I use a big pot filled with water and then stick in my oven with the oven light left on- usually overnight. </p>\n<p>I also freeze a portion of my yogurt (or a store bought one) to use as my starter. One tablespoon per &#8216;cube&#8217; and I use two &#8216;cubes&#8217; per litre of milk. I leave it out to thaw when I&#8217;m heating up my milk. <br />Although you can just save back a bit of yogurt from each batch to use at your starter, I found over time, after a few batches, it can get a bit pursed-lips tangy for my taste.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=66869#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-66869\", \"66869\", \"respond\", \"13152\")