ar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\"><a href='http://dayuntoday.wordpress.com/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>dayuntoday</a></cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/#comment-66957\">07.21.12 at 5:02 pm</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>I do this all the time, making a gallon about every other week.  I actually don&#8217;t bother with the mason jars&#8211;just pour the heated and cooled milk straight into the crock and whisk in the starter.  I preheat it for 10 min. or so first. I am careful not to get it too hot so that it won&#8217;t kill the starter.  Then I wrap a beach towel around the crock pot to insulate, and leave it overnight.  My daughter has a crock pot that came with an insulated carrying case, which is even handier.  Works like a charm, and SO much cheaper than buying yogurt, especially for the amount I use.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=66957#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-66957\", \"66957\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\n\t<li class=\"comment even thread-even depth-1\" id=\"comment-66969\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\"><a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/1116982002021