/div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>Anon &#8211; I wouldn&#8217;t suggest trying to use the milk again because if any rogue bacteria had gotten in there and incubated for 14 hours, you will have a bad case of food poisoning on your hands.  My only guess is that perhaps the milk didn&#8217;t cool enough before adding the yogurt (if it was too hot it could have killed the bacteria) or the type of yogurt used didn&#8217;t actually have live cultures (some yogurts don&#8217;t, surprisingly).  I definitely prefer the thermometer method because you have more control over the temperatures and when the starter is added.  Sorry to hear it didn&#8217;t work out for you!</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=70349#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-70349\", \"70349\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\n\t<li class=\"comment even thread-even depth-1\" id=\"comment-70359\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\">Anonymous</cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/#comment-70359\">10.31.12 at 1:16 pm</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>I also had an experience where the overnight incubation temp was a little too low, and the final product was sort of like a stringy mucous. So I have found that too hot = grainy and separated, while too cold = stringy mucousy. Will keep trying&#8230;</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=70359#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-70359\", \"70359\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\n\t<li class=\"comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1\" id=\"comment-71235\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/41dc3e007986c35dc46763689fa93174?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\"><a href='http://www.blogger.com/profile/08157490638587428083' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nicolette/Nikki/Nik/N</a></cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/#comment-71235\">12.31.12 at 6:12 pm</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>I am experimenting at this very moment with a tiny batch of &#8216;who knows if this will work at all yogurt&#8217;. I am using 1 cup of Vitasoy soy milk and 1 Tbsp strawberry flavored Activia yogurt. I first heated the milk to about 110 deg. in a small pot, and then removed from heat and added the yogurt. Stirred in the yogurt and then poured into 2 small jars (old jam jars). I then set the sealed jars into my crock pot lined with a dish towel, which I had on the low setting to create a warm environment. After a while I checked the temp and it was close to 120 deg. I think this may have killed my bacteria. It is now sitting in the crock which I turned off. It has been almost 3 hours and no sign of thickening. We&#8217;ll see. I am planing on trying with regular milk and plain probiotic yogurt for a starter, but these were the only things I had on hand and was just curious as to how it might turn out.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=71235#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-71235\", \"71235\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\n\t<li class=\"comment even thread-even depth-1\" id=\"comment-82288\">\n\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-header\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-author vcard\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/c5b84aa3e226bb58317f40cc314c1873?s=48&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D48&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />\t\t\t\t<cite class=\"fn\">Kevin</cite> <span class=\"says\">says:</span>\t\t \t</div>\n\n\t\t\t<div class=\"comment-meta commentmetadata\">\n\t\t\t\t<a href=\"http://www.budgetbytes.com/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/#comment-82288\">07.01.13 at 8:20 am</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"comment-content\">\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>Hey Beth!</p>\n<p>Great site.  It&#8217;s giving this 31 year old bachelor who&#8217;s attempting to actually learn how to cook some great inspiration (I really like the pictorial steps).  Anyways, I&#8217;m a dairy farmer and have access to raw whole milk.  Seeing as it&#8217;s unpasteurized would the heating to 185 Deg-F be enough to kill any potential harmful bacteria or should I take additional steps?  I&#8217;ve read a bit on home pasteurization which recommends heating  to a certain temperature (depending on the quick or slow method) then rapidly cooling to 40 Deg-F.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class=\"reply\">\n\t\t\t<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2012/07/how-to-make-yogurt/?replytocom=82288#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm(\"comment-82288\", \"82288\", \"respond\", \"13152\")'>Reply</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<ul class=\"children\">\n\n